Date: Thu 7 April 2011
Source: The Times of India, Times News Network (TNN) [edited]
http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-07/goa/29392200_1_chilli-crop-disease-sattari


Chili crop hit by viral disease
-------------------------------
Farmers in Sattari [North Goa district] have urged the government to
intervene and take steps to eradicate the viral disease, locally known
as Karpo, which is badly affecting the chili [_Capsicum_ sp.] crop in
various parts.

Scientists from the Indian Council for Agricultural Research in Old
Goa have collected samples and identified the disease as viral. In
earlier seasons, tomato and brinjal [aubergine] plants were also
affected by the disease. However, this year, the disease has affected
the chili plant.

The local agriculture officer said, "We have treatment available for
bacterial and fungal diseases. But, as Karpo is a new viral disease,
so far our office does not have any solution for the disease." He has
planned to undertake a survey to assess the losses suffered by farmers
due to the disease and send a proposal to seek compensation from the
government for the affected persons.

[Byline: Rajendra P Kerkar]

