[Around 20 viruses are known to infect capsicum causing yield
reduction and/or loss of fruit quality. Several of them are
transmitted by insect vectors (for example, aphids or thrips).
Solanaceous weeds may serve as pathogen reservoirs. Disease management
is difficult, especially under open field conditions, and usually
requires an integrated approach including vector control,
phytosanitation, cultural measures, as well as certified clean seed or
planting material. Crop varieties with different levels of resistance
to several of the viruses are available, but a clear diagnosis of the
specific virus(es) involved would be required in order to select
suitable cultivars for Goa.

While capsicum viruses often also affect related solanaceous hosts
such as tomato and aubergine, this is not proof that the problems in
Goa in earlier seasons on these crops were due to the same pathogen.

